<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="283" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[138,1022,1118,1494]" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">
This Palearctic species is widespread in central-northern Europe. Its distribution area ranges from Germany to Sweden, and from The Netherlands to Russia (European part) with the most southern record from Georgia. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Edwardsiana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sociabilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Edwardsiana sociabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents one of the rare documented cases in which specialized native leafhoppers have shifted to exotic shrubs, such as 
<taxonomicName box="[638,773,1295,1318]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rosa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rugosa">
<emphasis box="[638,773,1295,1318]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Rosa rugosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
,but in natural habitats it is confined to the tall herb 
<taxonomicName authority="Nickel 2008" authorityName="Nickel" authorityYear="2008" box="[454,832,1324,1348]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Filipendula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ulmaria">
<emphasis box="[454,670,1324,1348]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Filipendula ulmaria</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Nickel, H." box="[686,824,1324,1348]" editor="Floren, A." journalOrPublisher="Basic and applied studies from the high frontier. Bioform entomology &amp; equipment" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" pagination="175 - 214" refString="Nickel, H. 2008. Tracking the elusive: leafhoppers and planthoppers (Insecta: Hemiptera) in tree canopies of European deciduous forests. - In: Floren, A. &amp; Schmidl, J. (eds), Canopy arthropod research in Europe. Basic and applied studies from the high frontier. Bioform entomology &amp; equipment, pp. 175 - 214." title="Tracking the elusive: leafhoppers and planthoppers (Insecta: Hemiptera) in tree canopies of European deciduous forests" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Canopy arthropod research in Europe" year="2008">Nickel 2008</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This species frequently occurs in urban areas on 
<taxonomicName box="[486,539,1354,1377]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rosa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[486,539,1354,1377]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Rosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp., which is one of the most frequently cultivated genera among garden plants. The presence of this leafhopper in gardens was expected in Switzerland as the species occurs in Germany and Austria (
<bibRefCitation author="Nickel, H." bookContentInfo="460 pp." journalOrPublisher="Pensoft, Sofia and Moscow" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" refString="Nickel, H. 2003. The leafhoppers and planthoppers of Germany (Hemiptera, Auchenorrhyncha): patterns and strategies in a highly diverse group of phytophagous insects. - Pensoft, Sofia and Moscow, 460 pp." title="The leafhoppers and planthoppers of Germany (Hemiptera, Auchenorrhyncha): patterns and strategies in a highly diverse group of phytophagous insects" type="book" year="2003">Nickel 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Considering that leafhoppers in gardens have hardly been investigated in Switzerland, it is not surprising that 
<taxonomicName box="[529,661,1470,1494]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Edwardsiana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sociabilis">
<emphasis box="[529,661,1470,1494]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">E. sociabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not previously been found.
</paragraph>
